<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-128-124  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 124.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 18 1989 v3 n38 p71(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Report finds low pay chases employees from government.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zall, Milton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The President's Advisory Committee on Federal Pay issued a reportin Aug 1989 showing that the government is losing out to theprivate sector in attracting entry- and mid-level employees.andP;  Theproblem is blamed on low government salaries.andP;  There is an averagedifference of 28 percent between private- and public-sector pay.andO;Government salaries have not kept pace with either the ConsumerPrice Index nor the Bureau of Labor Statistics' Employment CostIndex.andP;  The committee recommends a 10 percent hike in governmentwages in 1990, and again in 1991.andP;  The productivity of federalemployees sunk to its lowest numbers in 1986 and 1987.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     National GovernmentSalaryReportsPersonnel ProblemsUnited States. Bureau of Labor Statistics.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>